@iantelegram1 and I talked about an extension of RIP-7859 (https://github.com/ethereum/RIPs/pull/57/files) that would allow the sequencer to subscribe to arbitrary storage slots / contract roots on L1 and other L2s using the same mechanism that secures RIP-7859. If you can fault-prove against an L1 Block Hash posted in L1OriginSource by the sequencer, then you can theoretically fault-prove against any storage slot on the L1, and therefore any L2 State Root, and therefore any arbitrary contract storage root on that L2.

If you combined that extended functionality with a canonical message box on each chain, then each sequencer could just subscribe to the contract storage root of the canonical messenger on each other chain. That reduces the proof size substantially when compared to proving all the way from the L1 Block Hash, especially if you optimize the packing of the storage layout. You have to deal with finality questions ‚Äî maybe the sequencer would only post finalized blocks wrt the view of the L1, but it would work and be much cheaper. 

You could do something similarly if you extended L1SLOAD to allow for even deeper calls through the L2 Block Hash outputs on the L1 via L2SLOAD. That would allow any user to request the finalized state of an L2 with respect to L1, and the sequencer could just return the value in the VM without needing to construct the MPT inclusion proof. The problem with this is that then each sequencer needs to maintain a view of the entire state of each other rollup it allows L2SLOADS from. Extending RIP-7859 means they only need to maintain a view of the message box on each chain.

BTW talking about guidelines for RIPs; 
@wilsoncusack, 7755 is actually more a "request for comment" than an "core improvement proposal" so it could be considered as the first "RRC" ( it's even cited as such in in the guideline RIP). So if you are ok with this you could update the category in the repo. 

